The Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) released its monthly Employment Situation Report, which showed strong employment and wage growth in July. Total nonfarm payroll employment increased by 164,000 jobs, in line with market expectations. The average pace of job growth over the past year has been 187,000 jobs per month, higher than anticipated. Since the President was elected, over 6.2 million jobs have been added to the economy. Job gains have surpassed 100,000 jobs in 29 of the 32 months since the President's election. The education and health services industry led job growth in July, followed by professional and business services. Manufacturing jobs also increased, with the industry adding 16,000 jobs in July. Wages continued to grow, with nominal average hourly earnings rising 3.2 percent over the past 12 months. The unemployment rate remained at 3.7 percent, marking the 17th consecutive month at or below 4 percent. The African American unemployment rate remained at 6.0 percent, and the African-American teen unemployment rate dropped to its lowest rate since 1972. The labor force participation rate increased slightly, and the Trump Administration's pro-growth policies continue to foster a strong economy.